What is a Constructor?

A constructor is a special function that is called automatically when an object is created.

Think of it like this:

When a baby is born, it immediately gets a name, birth certificate, etc.

Similarly, when an object is created, the constructor can initialize it.

Without a constructor
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student
{
public:
    string name;
    int age;
};

int main()
{
    Student s1;

    s1.name = "Ishan";
    s1.age = 20;

    cout << s1.name << " " << s1.age;
}

Here, you create the object first, then assign values.

With a constructor
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student
{
public:
    string name;
    int age;

    Student()
    {
        name = "Unknown";
        age = 0;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Student s1;

    cout << s1.name << " " << s1.age;
}

Output:

Unknown 0

Notice something?

You never called:

Student();

The compiler called it automatically when s1 was created.

Why is it called a constructor?

Because it constructs (initializes) the object.

Rules for Constructors

A constructor:

Has the same name as the class.
Has no return type (not even void).
Is called automatically.

Example:

class Student
{
public:
    Student()
    {
        cout << "Constructor Called";
    }
};

Creating an object:

Student s1;

Output:

Constructor Called
Parameterized Constructor

You can pass values while creating the object.

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student
{
public:
    string name;
    int age;

    Student(string n, int a)
    {
        name = n;
        age = a;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Student s1("Ishan", 20);

    cout << s1.name << " " << s1.age;
}

Output:

Ishan 20

This is much cleaner than assigning values after creation.

What is a Destructor?

A destructor is another special member function.

It is called automatically when an object is destroyed.

Think of it like cleaning up after you're done using something.

Example:

class Student
{
public:
    Student()
    {
        cout << "Constructor\n";
    }

    ~Student()
    {
        cout << "Destructor\n";
    }
};
int main()
{
    Student s1;
}

Output:

Constructor
Destructor

Why?

s1 is created → constructor runs.
main() ends, s1 goes out of scope → destructor runs.
Destructor Rules

A destructor:

Has the same name as the class.
Starts with ~.
Has no return type.
Takes no parameters.
Is called automatically.

Example:

~Student()
{
}
Constructor vs Destructor
Constructor	Destructor
Called when an object is created	Called when an object is destroyed
Initializes the object	Cleans up resources
Same name as the class	Same name with ~ before it
Can have parameters	Cannot have parameters
Why are destructors useful?

Suppose you allocate memory:

Student *s = new Student;

Later:

delete s;

When delete s; runs:

The destructor executes.
The memory is freed.

That's why destructors are especially important when a class manages resources like dynamic memory, files, or network connections.

Flow of execution
Program Starts
      │
      ▼
Student s1;
      │
      ▼
Constructor Called
      │
      ▼
Use Object
      │
      ▼
Object Goes Out of Scope
      │
      ▼
Destructor Called
For now, remember these three ideas:
Class = Blueprint
Object = Instance of the blueprint
Constructor = Automatically initializes the object when it's created.
Destructor = Automatically cleans up when the object is destroyed.
